05796nam a22008175i 9780691190518DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911905187 a10.1515/97806911905182doi  a(DE-B1597)501826  a(OCoLC)1076425828  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE185.61b.S616 2006eb 7aPOL0400402bisacsh04a369/.3960732231 aSkocpol, Theda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat a Mighty Power We Can Be :bAfrican American Fraternal Groups and the Struggle for Racial Equality /cTheda Skocpol, Marshall Ganz, Ariane Liazos. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in American Politics: Historical, International, and Comparative Perspectives ;v16900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tTABLES -- tPREFACE -- tCHAPTER ONE. African American Fraternalism A Missing Chapter in the Story of U.S. Civic Democracy -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Panorama of African American Fraternal Federations -- tCHAPTER THREE. African American Fraternals as Schools for Democracy -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Proprietors, Helpmates, and Pilgrims in Black and White Fraternal Rituals -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Defending the Legal Right to Organize -- tCHAPTER SIX. Black Fraternalists and the Mid-Twentieth-Century Movement for Civil Rights -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. The Achievements of African American Fraternalism -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX -- tPRINCETON STUDIES IN AMERICAN POLITICS: HISTORICAL, INTERNATIONAL, AND COMPARATIVE PERSPECTIVES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the nineteenth through the mid-twentieth centuries, millions of American men and women participated in fraternal associations--self-selecting brotherhoods and sisterhoods that provided aid to members, enacted group rituals, and engaged in community service. Even more than whites did, African Americans embraced this type of association; indeed, fraternal lodges rivaled churches as centers of black community life in cities, towns, and rural areas alike. Using an unprecedented variety of secondary and primary sources--including old documents, pictures, and ribbon-badges found in eBay auctions--this book tells the story of the most visible African American fraternal associations. The authors demonstrate how African American fraternal groups played key roles in the struggle for civil rights and racial integration. Between the 1890s and the 1930s, white legislatures passed laws to outlaw the use of important fraternal names and symbols by blacks. But blacks successfully fought back. Employing lawyers who in some cases went on to work for the NAACP, black fraternalists took their cases all the way to the Supreme Court, which eventually ruled in their favor. At the height of the modern Civil Rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s, they marched on Washington and supported the lawsuits through lobbying and demonstrations that finally led to legal equality. This unique book reveals a little-known chapter in the story of civic democracy and racial equality in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American fraternal organizationsxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocieties, etcxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocieties, etc.xHistory. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Local.2bisacsh1 aCamp, Bayliss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanz, Marshall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKent, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 